# .NET Framework → .NET 8 Migration: `EventProcessor`

## Critical Issues in the Original Code

| Issue | Why It Breaks on .NET 8 |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** — removed entirely in .NET 5+ |
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | Still exists but unreliable — only interrupts managed blocking calls, not `WaitOne` on all platforms |
| `ManualResetEvent` + `Queue` + `lock` | Unnecessary complexity — `BlockingCollection<T>` or `Channel<T>` replace this entire pattern |
| Race condition | Multiple `Enqueue` calls between `WaitOne`/`Reset` lose all but one item |
| No graceful shutdown | No cancellation token support |

## Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
using System.Threading.Channels;

public class EventProcessor : IAsyncDisposable
{
    private readonly Channel<string> _channel = Channel.CreateUnbounded<string>();
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private Task? _processingTask;

    public void Start()
    {
        _processingTask = Task.Run(() => RunLoopAsync(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task RunLoopAsync(CancellationToken ct)
    {
        try
        {
            await foreach (var item in _channel.Reader.ReadAllAsync(ct))
            {
                Handle(item);
            }
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (ct.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            // Graceful shutdown — drain remaining items if desired
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        if (!_channel.Writer.TryWrite(item))
            throw new InvalidOperationException("Channel is closed.");
    }

    public async ValueTask StopAsync(TimeSpan? timeout = null)
    {
        _channel.Writer.Complete();           // signal no more items
        _cts.CancelAfter(timeout ?? TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5)); // hard deadline

        if (_processingTask is not null)
            await _processingTask;
    }

    public async ValueTask DisposeAsync()
    {
        await StopAsync();
        _cts.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item)
    {
        // your processing logic
    }
}
```

## Key Migration Decisions

### 1. `Channel<T>` replaces `ManualResetEvent` + `Queue` + `lock`
The original code reimplements a producer-consumer queue manually. `Channel<T>` is purpose-built for this, is lock-free internally, and handles backpressure.

### 2. `CancellationToken` replaces `Thread.Abort()`/`Interrupt()`
```csharp
// ❌ .NET Framework — throws PlatformNotSupportedException on .NET 8
_thread.Abort();

// ✅ .NET 8 — cooperative cancellation
_cts.Cancel();
```

### 3. The original race condition is fixed
```
// Original bug: two rapid Enqueue() calls → only one Dequeue()
//   Thread A: Enqueue("a") → Set()
//   Thread B: Enqueue("b") → Set()   ← signal already set, no extra wake
//   Loop:    WaitOne → Reset → Dequeue → handles "a" → WaitOne (blocks)
//   "b" is stuck in the queue until the next enqueue
```
`Channel<T>.ReadAllAsync()` yields every item — no signal can be lost.

### 4. `Task` replaces `Thread`
Dedicated threads are rarely needed. `Task.Run` uses the thread pool and integrates with `async`/`await`. If you need a dedicated long-running thread:
```csharp
_processingTask = Task.Factory.StartNew(
    () => RunLoopAsync(_cts.Token),
    TaskCreationOptions.LongRunning).Unwrap();
```

## Alternative: Synchronous-Only Variant

If your codebase can't adopt `async` yet:

```csharp
using System.Collections.Concurrent;

public class EventProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly BlockingCollection<string> _queue = new();
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private Thread? _thread;

    public void Start()
    {
        _thread = new Thread(RunLoop) { IsBackground = true };
        _thread.Start();
    }

    private void RunLoop()
    {
        try
        {
            foreach (var item in _queue.GetConsumingEnumerable(_cts.Token))
                Handle(item);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) { }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item) => _queue.Add(item);

    public void Stop()
    {
        _queue.CompleteAdding();
        if (!_thread?.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5)) ?? false)
            _cts.Cancel(); // force exit from GetConsumingEnumerable
    }

    public void Dispose() { Stop(); _cts.Dispose(); _queue.Dispose(); }
    private void Handle(string item) { }
}
```

## Quick Reference

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 Replacement |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | `CancellationToken` checked in loops |
| `ManualResetEvent` + `Queue` | `Channel<T>` or `BlockingCollection<T>` |
| `new Thread(...)` | `Task.Run(...)` (usually) |
| `thread.Join(ms)` | `await task` with timeout via `CancellationToken` |
